</md></sn><sn><md>## Components of an Earthquake{.text-center}

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Fault-zone{.text-center}
A fault-zone is a fractured area in the Earth’s crust where blocks of rock move past each other. Earthquakes usually occur along these fault lines due to the sudden release of stress.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
![diagram](https://asapeducate.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/EPICENTER.jpg)
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Hypocenter (Focus){.text-center}
The hypocenter, also called the focus, is the exact point inside the Earth where the earthquake originates. It is the location of the initial rupture.
:::

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Epicenter{.text-center}
The epicenter is the point on the Earth’s surface that lies directly above the hypocenter. It is usually the area where the effects of the earthquake are felt most strongly.
:::

:::

:::.row

:::.col-12 .col-lg-6
### Seismic Waves{.text-center}

Seismic waves are energy waves that spread out from the hypocenter during an earthquake. They are of two main types:

* **Body Waves** – Travel through the Earth’s interior.

  * **P-waves (Primary waves):** The fastest waves, move in a push-pull motion, can travel through solids, liquids, and gases.
  * **S-waves (Secondary waves):** Slower than P-waves, move in a side-to-side motion, can only travel through solids.

* **Surface Waves** – Travel along the Earth’s surface and usually cause the most destruction.

  * They move more slowly but with greater amplitude, producing strong ground shaking.
:::

